%I A397474 #15 Jul 15 2026 11:00:24
%S A397474 0,0,1,0,6,1,1,3,3,6,6,9,4,3,9,9,12,6,12,9,15,3,12,13,3,15,6,15,9,25,
%T A397474 3,18,33,3,21,3,24,8,3,27,48,11,3,30,3,33,17,3,36,54,40,3,39,16,3,42,
%U A397474 3,45,48,29,3,48,33,25,6,18,102,9,138,3,51,20,3,54
%N A397474 a(1) = 0. For n > 1, a(n) is the number of ways to write a(n-1) as the product of two previous terms with distinct indices.
%C A397474 A variant of A394611 based on products instead of sums.
%C A397474 This sequence is unbounded. Proof: Seeking a contradiction, suppose that all terms are < M, hence some value, say v, must appear infinitely often; we can write a(k_1) = ... = a(k_M) = v with 3 < k_1 < ... < k_M; as a(3)*a(k_1) = ... = a(3)*a(k_M) = v = a(k_M), a(k_M+1) >= M: a contradiction.
%C A397474 The sequence does not contain the value 2: the first eight terms, 0, 0, 1, 0, 6, 1, 1, 3, contain three 1's (none at the last index), no 2's, hence for any n >= 8, the products of terms at distinct indexes (3, n), (6, n) and (7, n) equal a(n), and a(n+1) >= 3 > 2.
%C A397474 Will all integers except 2 appear in the sequence?
%C A397474 The value 3*n follows the n-th value 3.
%C A397474 For any prime number p > 3, the value 3 follows the first multiple of p, if any.
%H A397474 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A397474/b397474.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A397474 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A397474/a397474.gp.txt">PARI program</a>
%F A397474 a(n+2) <= A000217(n).
%e A397474 The initial terms, alongside the corresponding products, are:
%e A397474   n   a(n)  Products
%e A397474   --  ----  -------------------------------------------------------------------
%e A397474    1     0  N/A
%e A397474    2     0  None
%e A397474    3     1  a(1)*a(2)
%e A397474    4     0  None
%e A397474    5     6  a(1)*a(2), a(1)*a(3), a(1)*a(4), a(2)*a(3), a(2)*a(4), a(3)*a(4)
%e A397474    6     1  a(3)*a(5)
%e A397474    7     1  a(3)*a(6)
%e A397474    8     3  a(3)*a(6), a(3)*a(7), a(6)*a(7)
%e A397474    9     3  a(3)*a(8), a(6)*a(8), a(7)*a(8)
%e A397474   10     6  a(3)*a(8), a(3)*a(9), a(6)*a(8), a(6)*a(9), a(7)*a(8), a(7)*a(9)
%e A397474   11     6  a(3)*a(5), a(3)*a(10), a(5)*a(6), a(5)*a(7), a(6)*a(10), a(7)*a(10)
%o A397474 (PARI) \\ See Links section.
%o A397474 (Python)
%o A397474 from collections import Counter
%o A397474 from itertools import islice
%o A397474 def A397474_gen(): # generator of terms
%o A397474     alst, an, c = [], 0, Counter()
%o A397474     while True:
%o A397474         an = c[an]
%o A397474         yield an
%o A397474         c.update(an*ai for ai in alst)
%o A397474         alst.append(an)
%o A397474 print(list(islice(A397474_gen(), 83))) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Jun 27 2026
